In 2017, Michigan police seized property from nearly 1,000 people who were never convicted of a crime.
Those spreadsheets also showed that police, particularly in Wayne County, Michigan, seized thousands of cars in 2017 under the auspices of marijuana enforcement.
Michigan law enforcement is pushing back against the reform efforts.
Two changes to Michigan law, Nelson says, "opened the floodgates" for civil asset forfeiture in the state.
Of the total 2,078 cash seizures by Michigan law enforcement in 2017, the median value was $396, and the average value was $2,042.